<subsection xml:id="subsection-1-1-1">
  <title>Graphs of Quadratic Equations</title>

  <p> A quadratic equation, like any real-valued function, can be graphed on
    the Cartesian plane. It turns out that figures called parabolas, which are
    geometric curves defined by things called directrices and foci (don't
    worry about it), are modeled by quadratic equations. Recall from your
    algebra studies that a parabola is that U-shaped curve that can open
    upward or downward. Here are some perfectly good parabolas below. 
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="quad-graphs">
    <caption>Three parabolas.
    <latex /></caption>
    <image width="80%" xml:id="quads">
    <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}
          \draw[&lt;->,thick](-5,0)--(5,0);
          \draw[&lt;->, thick](0,-4)--(0,4);
          \draw(-.3,3.8) node{$y$};
          \draw(4.8,.3) node{$x$};
          \draw[domain=.17:4.98,smooth,variable=\x,blue,&lt;->, thick] plot ({\x},{0.5*\x*\x - 3*\x + 4.5});
          \draw[domain=-3.45:1.45,smooth,variable=\x,red,&lt;->, thick] plot ({\x},{-0.8*\x*\x - 1.6*\x });
          \draw[domain=-3.412:-0.582,smooth,variable=\x,orange,&lt;->, thick] plot ({\x},{1.5*\x*\x + 6*\x + 7});
          \node[rotate=-51, blue] at (2,1) {$f(x)$};
          \node[rotate=59, red] at (-2.2,-1) {$g(x)$};
          \node[rotate=76, orange] at (-1.1,3) {$h(x)$};
          \filldraw[red](0,0) circle(2.1pt);
          \filldraw[red](-2,0) circle(2.1pt);
          \filldraw[blue](3,0) circle(2.1pt);
        \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
    </image>
  </figure>

  <p>
    Algebraically, whether a parabola opens upward or downward depends on the coefficient of the $x^2$ term in the parabola's equation.  
    In the equation <m>y=ax^2+bx+c</m>, the parabola will open upward if $a>0$ and downward if $a&lt;0$.  
    (If $a=0$, the we have a line rather than a parabola.)
  </p>

  <p>
    For many parabolas, some points of interest include the points where the curve intersects the <m>x</m>-axis.  
    For a quadratic equation <m>ax^2 + bx+c</m> representing such a parabola, the <m>x</m>-values of those points would be the solutions to <m>ax^2 + bx + c = 0</m>.
    The solutions to such an equation are called the \textit{roots} of the equation. 
    As can be seen in the above figure, not all quadratic equations have roots as not all parabolas intersect the $x$-axis.  
    Further, some quadratic equations only have one root. 
  </p>  
</subsection>